What is needed instead here is the launch of a debate about the extent to which the substantially increased wealth generation throughout the European economy, which must be considered separately from demographic change, should make a solidarity-based contribution to the European social model.
I have abstained from voting on Amendment 8, since while I do recognise that the problem of a brain drain from developing countries into Europe is a very serious one, I distrust the motivation of the ITS Group in tabling this amendment.
We must strive to prevent highly educated people from leaving their own countries in massive numbers, thereby causing economic damage, but it should certainly not be about opposing immigration into Europe by definition.
